{
  "doc_id": "11135",
  "text": "The most common methods to solve fault diagnosis problems in literature have been developed using supervised learning approaches, i.e. learning the underlying patterns from the previously observed condition monitoring data with known labels from different fault types. Examples of such approaches include Support Vector Machines (SVM) [CITATION_1] and different types of deep learning algorithms, such as convolutional neural networks (CNN) [CITATION_2] and Long Short-Term Memory Networks (LSTM) [CITATION_3] . Supervised learning approaches, however, will perform poorly when applied to newly evolving faults since the underlying patterns will be dissimilar to those learned.",
